'}, {'created': '2015-10-01 20:27:47.000000000', 'message': 'Expand endpoint filters to service providers

Endpoint filtering is a keystone extension since the Havana release,
in Juno it was expanded by the Multi-Attribute Endpoint Grouping
spec that improves the filtering flexibility.

Since Kilo, we added the concept of Service Providers to keystone,
the list of such resources is returned in the token alongside the
service catalog.
In Liberty we are proposing to extend endpoints filtering to also
support Service Providers. This should not bring API nor model
changes, just extra checks to the endpoint filter controller/backend.

bp service-provider-filters

Co-Authored-By: Iury Gregory Melo Ferreira <iurygregory@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ice20ede8a27eefad1a98d810dfee425a71d06a86

commit_message:
Expand endpoint filters to service providers

Endpoint filtering is a keystone extension since the Havana release,
in Juno it was expanded by the Multi-Attribute Endpoint Grouping
spec that improves the filtering flexibility.

Since Kilo, we added the concept of Service Providers to keystone,
the list of such resources is returned in the token alongside the
service catalog.
In Mitaka we are proposing to extend endpoints filtering to also
support Service Providers. This should not bring API nor model
changes, just extra checks to the endpoint filter controller/backend.

bp service-provider-filters

Co-Authored-By: Marek Denis <marek.denis@cern.ch>
Co-Authored-By: Iury Gregory Melo Ferreira <iurygregory@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ice20ede8a27eefad1a98d810dfee425a71d06a86

commit_message:
Encrypt default hidden parameters correctly

Default values of parameters are not guaranteed to be strings
which causes encryption to fail.

Change-Id: Iee814d7bac8bb3af4c12c3af1c69d5ddab4c7664
Closes-Bug: #1488679

commit_message:
Removing notification_driver line in neutron.conf

An extra notification_driver line slipped into neutron.conf in a recent
commit and it references a variable that isn't being set.

Closes-bug: 1523654
Related-bug: 1522506

Change-Id: I279ca231f668c229f5eb93230b26f0c8502db0a9

commit_message:
Return link added in network detail page

In network detail page there is no return link
to come back to the network list.

This patch adding the breadcrumb in the
network detail page to get the return link.

Change-Id: I014aa77eb4c4647a8f333726bcd12c99e9f913e2
Closes-Bug: #1523860

commit_message:
Exclude pyudev 0.18

Version 0.18 changed raised exception for one of its function, thus
breaking ironic-python-agent gate - see bug #1522756
But this exception was only introduced is 0.18 thus making a proper
upgrade path unclear.

Upstream issue reported:
https://github.com/pyudev/pyudev/issues/129

Change-Id: I1a0cf61b1ad17497752a84a4a5da565726582e01

commit_message:
Ensure WMIException message includes the original WMI exc msg

At the moment, the original WMI exception message is lost if an
exception message is passed, which is not desired behavior.

This patch fixes the issue.

Change-Id: I9c00380b7591322f27f59b13a35f3e3124dfba5f

commit_message:
[Sahara] Get urls of datasources safer

There are possible problems with retrieving datasources urls,
we can avoid that if we will wrap retrieving with try/except block.

Closes-bug: 1502854
Change-Id: I17599a8559dc0a7e33d1f70033000a01d5396dc6

commit_message:
Adds Hyper-V vNic hot-plug implementation

The new Hyper-V version adds support for adding and removing
vNICs on a running instance.

This is a driver feature parity blueprint.

Implementation is straightforward and consists in providing the
virt driver's class attach_interface and detach_interface methods.

Implements: blueprint hyper-v-vnic-hot-plug

Change-Id: I14aba8b14b7036a09a8dde8235fd4345af4da510

commit_message:
Add order check in fuel log_step.

The ordering is meaningfull and can mislead in log investigation.
Simple counter added.

Change-Id: I3c2ace4bc0f6d0722a40a0a32086c83f96b7494d
Closes-bug: #1515610

commit_message:
Remove dynamic routing db tables

Remove the following db tables:
- midonet_advertise_route
- midonet_routing_peers
- midonet_routing_instances

Expand db migration chain should be safe because
these db tables haven't had the corresponding db models.

Partial-Bug: #1522687
Partial-Bug: #1521519
Change-Id: I64380b819c89655ef42aaca2faa14166057ee137

commit_message:
New repository to store data regarding Fuel Plugins CI

Purpose of this repository is to store puppet manifests, jenkins jobs
(yamls), python and shell code related to building a CI process in
partner's environments.

Change-Id: Ic3c86cc82ed8b6862e6695b347eb380005246691
Closes-Bug: #1522399

commit_message:
Add notifier taskflow extraction library

This library/chunk of code is extracted out of
taskflow and moved to be its own independent
library (it shares the same license as taskflow
and will likely soon be an oslo library).

Code is at (for now):

https://github.com/harlowja/notifier

This is needed for review:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228892/

Docs are at (for now):

http://notifier.readthedocs.org/

----

Is the library actively maintained?

Yes.

Is the library good code?

Obviously yes.

Is the library python 3 compatible?

Yes.

Is the library license compatible?

Yes.

Is the library already packaged in the distros we target?

No (not directly, they package taskflow, where
this code came from).

Is the function of this library already covered by
other libraries in global-requirements.txt?

No.

Change-Id: If63e54b4eee77361a4c5c53b724db0f600fddd37

commit_message:
Bump ddt version to >=1.0.1

Some tests may be skipped silently when using earlier versions with
testr and Mock instances in data. More details may be found by the
following link: https://github.com/txels/ddt/issues/35

Change-Id: I78286cb941f5f562f8f425a7ff24b4ac724f375e

commit_message:
Deprecate ldap Role

The LDAP backend for assignment and resource drivers has been
deprecated since the 'K' release. It's been decided that its time
to deprecate LDAP role, since without the support for assignment
and resource, the role backend is likely broken.

The LDAP role backend was split from assignment backend and should
have also been deprecated according to the agreement from the keystone
team, but it looks like it was missed [1].

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack/2015-January/011337.html

Change-Id: I390f5c2fb36d617a83fce618708febca3da9f1d2
implements: bp deprecated-as-of-mitaka

commit_message:
Do not assign a value to the class variable 'widget'

Class variable 'widget' stores a default widget for CharField.
It is dangerous to change it. This patch fixes this and assigns
a value to instance variable.

Change-Id: I7220dcacd64aeee096e9340dc49bb4c5ebcfefd5
Closes-Bug: #1521535

I want to do some more complicated testing with SAML assertions, however
I can't read the XML snippets as they are or have any chance of
modifying them.

Extract the SAML fixtures into template files that I can reuse again
later.

commit_message:
Make cluster-resize return a location header

Cluster-resize response should contain a location header
and action_id, the action_id is consumed by client side.

Change-Id: Ie9950b9045d54be679285bd875df0efe90696527
partial-blueprint: http-response-modification

commit_message:
Specify keystoneauth1 exception more

Currently all exceptions from keystoneauth1 are handled in the
same way, but not all the exceptions have http_status property,
so need to specify the exception types.

Change-Id: I410f31544e0cdbd4e3d8f6470fcc8c7ee4c46ff2
Closes-bug: #1522664

commit_message:
Split resource tests from assignment tests

As of Kilo release, the resource backend was
created from the assignment backend [1].

However, resource tests didn't follow that split.

This patch splits out resource tests from
test_v3_assignment.py to test_v3_resource.py.

[1] https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/keystone-specs/specs/kilo/pluggable_assignments.html

Co-Authored-By: Dave Chen <dave.jungler@gmail.com>
Partially Implements: bp pluggable-assignments

Change-Id: I9d639e892df021db93d10a9313c4f4d1df737fef

Though formally correct it is not clear from this description when should I use single environment and when not. The idea behind environment is that it is a single unit of deployment. You deploy environment, not application. Environments default shared entities like common Heat stack, networks that all applications share etc. If something is going on in environment then the whole environment gets busy. Applications in single environment can talk to each other while applications in different envs cannot (from MuranoPL point of view). Also, by default, environment creates network isolation boundaries because in default configuration there is a separate network per environment and apps in different environments are isolated from each other on network level'}, {'account_id': 7549, 'date': '2015-12-02 16:37:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Deprecate nova_admin_ options

nova_admin_* options are deprecated since Kilo, Keystone auth plugins mechanism
should be used instead. Added support for password(v2/v3) plugin

Change-Id: I7c2b75688051f81a9f8b61ef7ed34e00562ac31b

Assuming your naming scheme is "${image-name}-plugin-${plugin-name}", you could do something like:

  [nova-base-plugin-vmware-nsx]
  type = git
  location = https://github.com/openstack/vmware-nsx
  reference = master
  
  [nova-base-plugin-contrail-neutron-plugin]
  type = git

commit_message:
Allow fetching plugins as part of the build

This change allows additional archives to be fetched as part of the
build and added to images.

An example use case is the installation of plugins for neutron. For
example, to add the networking-arista plugin to neutron-server, one
would do the following in kolla-build.conf:

[neutron-server-plugin-networking-arista]
type = url
location = http://tarballs.openstack.org/networking-arista/networking-arista-master.tar.gz

The format for plugin sections is <image-name>-plugin-<plugin-name>

The required Dockerfile additions will be added in the next patchset.

Background to this change:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/207545/3/docker_templates/neutron/neutron-server/Dockerfile.j2

Related: blueprint neutron-third-party-plugins
DocImpact
Change-Id: Idec2ca9fd06163c7d820e8c4bc9ebca8d9673856

Remove required project_id from functional test templates

- Modify template data to reflect urls with no project id
- regenerate json files from doc api samples to new microversion
- Add project_id field to tests that define data within the function

commit_message:
Python3 readiness for congress/datalog

Result: all congress/tests/datalog/* tests pass. Under tox -epy34.

Changes:
- Replace by explicit logic many comparisons between different types
- Add __hash__ implementation wherever __eq__ is overridden
- Use explicit logic to choose type of div used (floor-div vs true-div)
- explicit conversion when joining dict to list
- Remove superfluous call to super(Fact, self).__init__ (compile.py:156)
- Use six.iteritems to unify items (py3) and iteritems (py2)
- Use six.moves.range instead of xrange
- Use six.string_types to unify ascii-string and unicode-string
- Use six.integer_types to unify int and long

Partially implements blueprint: support-python3

Change-Id: I81a7017f47106e97375039aa9f8a8aee978de1b0

I've been told before that the preferred way of submitting patches is to keep them very small and isolated, and in the case of small patches there is no need to create a separate blueprint or bug but instead simply document the change details within the patch-set itself.

Steven, can you please clarify the preferred work flow for the kolla project?

The work with the ubuntu vagrant support it is an on going process and I'm planning to keep the scripts up to date. In that case, should I be creating a new bug for every change request?"}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2015-12-01 16:16:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

> the preferred way of submitting patches is to keep them very small and isolated
I would say this is correct

>  in the case of small patches there is no need to create a separate blueprint or bug
Generally for small patches the workflow is to create a bug. If the patch is very small (like a one liner, spelling change, etc), you can add "TrivialFix" to your commit message and omit the bug. A blueprint is generally used in the case of larger functionality orientated changes.

--
Overall the change looks fine assuming you've tested. I think a quick bug ref would be useful here as others have suggested.'}, {'account_id': 13039, 'date': '2015-12-01 23:58:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Diogo, sorry for not paying more attention to your commit message in my initial review.

We do prefer all commits to have a related bug or blueprint in their commit message so that we can track work effectively, but it is not mandatory. Doc changes for example are exempted. Also, if your patch is very simple and you think it doesn't make sense to create a bug for it, you can simply add the TrivialFix tag in the commit message so we know there is no related bug. There is no rule dictating when we can use the TrivialFix tag, it's based on your appreciation.

In this case, I'm of the opinion it's a bit more than a trivial fix and it deserves a bug in launchpad."}, {'account_id': 19148, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:30:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the comment Martin.

OK, I'll create a bug to track this change and resubmit the patch."}, {'account_id': 19148, 'date': '2015-12-07 04:35:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-07 05:09:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

One inline comment.

But I have the one other question. Why we use Vidid at all? It's a standard release for desktop usage, not for servers. Shouldn't we use LTS (Trusty)?"}, {'account_id': 19148, 'date': '2015-12-07 15:18:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 19148, 'date': '2015-12-07 15:35:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Michal,
The latest version of docker requires kernel 3.19. Trusty comes with 3.13. I know that it is possible to update the kernel to 3.19 on Trusty but that requires a system reboot before finalizing the provision of the Ubuntu vagrant box which can throw first time starters off. 
On Vivid, the kernel 3.19 comes shipped out of the box. There are also some other updates on that release: https://wiki.ubuntu.com/VividVervet/ReleaseNotes

I'm not saying that kolla should recommend Vivid for production deployments. However, I don't see an issue for staying up to date with the community releases for a Vagrant dev box.

The ubuntu-bootstrap.sh script does have the conditional statement to update the kernel and reboot the box in case the kernel is not 3.19. We could add a note on the docs saying that if people want to use Trusty they can simply change the base box on the Vagrantfile and rerun the provision script after the reboot?

commit_message:
Update Vagrant's Ubuntu box provisioning script

Starting from Vivid Ubuntu uses systemd as the
default boot manager instead of upstart. Updating
the way the docker daemon is configured to follow
the systemd way.
Setting env variable GUNICORN_OPTS=[--preload]
to fix race condition and avoid IntegrityError
when pushing images to local registry

Change-Id: I841f85015c2c3683ef7e1e454ec1369263063c45
Related-bug: https://github.com/docker/docker-registry/issues/518
Closes-Bug: #1523336

commit_message:
Renaming Cinder admin client files

This patch renames:

1. tempest/services/volume/base/admin/base_volume_<client name>.py
   into tempest/services/volume/base/admin/base_<client name>.py.
Example:
    base_volume_types_client.py -> base_types_client.py

2. tempest/services/volume/v1/json/admin/volume_<client name>.py
   into tempest/services/volume/v1/json/admin/<client name>.py.
Example:
    volume_hosts_client.py -> hosts_client.py

3. tempest/services/volume/v2/json/admin/volume_<client name>.py
   into tempest/services/volume/v2/json/admin/<client name>.py.
Example:
    volume_quotas_client.py -> quotas_client.py

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I180525ce679a395fdd97a8f2dedb94e4851be43d

snapshot operation within the Hyper-V driver.

The alternative would be canceling pending WMI jobs when instance

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Lock snapshot operation using instance uuid

The instance snapshot operation is not synchronized withing the
compute manager.

Attempting to destroy an instance while it's being snapshoted fails
when using Hyper-V. This can lead to leaked instances.

In order to avoid this, this patch synchronizes the instance
snapshot operation within the Hyper-V driver.

The alternative would be canceling pending WMI jobs when instance
termination is requested, which we consider introducing as a later
effort.

Change-Id: I1ad3f795925503e59bf51ee3148871a88e9eecf0
Partial-Bug: #1461970
(cherry picked from commit 6d8903b5d9609305d63aba0067a032a66f5ce3ee)

commit_message:
Don't remove user from groups if groups don't change

If there is no change of 'groups' property when updating
a keystone user resource, do not remove the user from
the groups.

Change-Id: Ib8e920e6ef95d654d0641e8635bd586047c89047
Closes-Bug: #1522247

looks good!
however I tested and found two unexpected action.

1. In keypair, name which is displayed at breadcrumbs is fixed to "Key Pair Details". Other points are displayed a selected object name as far as I see

2. It is added a "(number)" at the end of breadcrumb.
For example, in the case of rule of "default", breadcrumb is below.

"Access & Security Manage Security Group Rules: default (2)"

then if I create new rule (name is "test"), breadcrumb will be 

"Access & Security Manage Security Group Rules: test (3)"

Is it as expected ?

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 12281, 'date': '2015-12-07 08:40:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

Hey Kenji!

Good comments, will recheck as indeed seems the wrong behavior.'}, {'account_id': 12281, 'date': '2015-12-07 08:48:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Workflow

Checked both:

 - For the first case, This is showing the details for one object with all the info below so I dont think it makes sense to show the object in the breadcrumb. In the case of the sec groups is different as you have "groups" and "rules" so when managing those "rules" is helpful to have a reminder on which "group" you are modifying stuff.
On a view of a single object is not really useful, specially having all the details already in the same page.


 - Second case, seems to be normal. It will add the ID if the security group to the breadcrumb. Im guessing this is done due to the fact that you can have several security groups with the same name, so you get hte ID to easily identify them.


Let me know if this resolves your questions :D'}, {'account_id': 12281, 'date': '2015-12-07 08:49:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Make breadcrumb appear on sec groups and keypair details

when editing security groups rules there is no button to
go back to the original page.
Same when looking at a keypair details.
This adds the breadcrumb to both pages so you can go
back to the original page.
Also modifies the test KeyPairViewTests.test_keypair_detail_get
to take into account the breadcrumbs

Change-Id: I2e804c46c744f2f6a30dc02026aa4801c69b06ac
Closes-Bug: #1519591

I'm pretty excited to see this show up. Although we've invested heavily in ansible tooling to roll our cluster one by one with requisite DB shutdowns and backups etc, that model won't work as well when we have Keystone in docker and we're upgrading every 2 weeks. +1 from me on the theory. I'm also +1 on this only working 1 release to the next (the model where you can stop using a column in release N and remove it in N+1)."}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2015-11-30 20:07:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

Couple more comments, I think this is coming along though!'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-11-30 20:14:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

Great write-up. I started to comment in the lines of what was spelled out in the alternatives section, then realized it was all spelled out there. Very nice.

I'm in favor of the expand/contract method rather then waiting multiple releases, hurting performance."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-11-30 20:36:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(6 comments)

I'd really prefer we went with the expand / contract approach for performance and security reasons. There should be a good reason to not take that approach. Once the keystones have been updated to the same level there should be no reason to keep the old cols around, and it shouldn't be too hard for deployers to keep their keystones in sync."}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-12-01 06:45:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(7 comments)

Some initial feedback.

I really like the idea of rolling upgrades. But it's kinda hard to comprehend the proposed changes without a good understanding on how rolling upgrade is achieved. Perhaps adding a section or reference link educating the reviewers before diving into the proposed changes? For example, how does old code work with the new schema? How does new code work with the old schema, or is that even a requirement? How are we keeping the two columns in sync?"}, {'account_id': 14250, 'date': '2015-12-01 11:12:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(15 comments)'}, {'account_id': 14250, 'date': '2015-12-01 11:13:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-01 11:17:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

- gate-keystone-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/86/245186/8/check/gate-keystone-specs-docs/c47b5fa//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 3m 02s
- gate-keystone-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/86/245186/8/check/gate-keystone-specs-python27/22ba4f7/ : SUCCESS in 2m 28s'}, {'account_id': 14250, 'date': '2015-12-01 14:19:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Brant

I don't think that the expand/contract approach does anything to mitigate the performance and security issues you mentioned. The only outcome is that changes to the schema migrations can be done after the upgrade, to remove stale data, instead of removing them in the next cycle. This would be a nice addition to get the job done in two, instead of three releases, but it doesn't touch the problem of data migration. In any case, to facilitate rolling upgrades, there has to be an interim release which knows how to migrate the data."}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-01 14:28:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14250, 'date': '2015-12-01 14:33:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

@guang-yee

Dan Smith has some good writeups about upgradability of Nova:
http://www.danplanet.com/blog/tag/upgrades/

But the primary focus of Nova is to have older computes running with a newer conductor, so he mainly goes into details of how versioned objects and RPC APIs work.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-12-01 17:44:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Grzegorz Grasza: the performance hit comes from having to read/write to two copies of columns for long periods of time. Its ok to do that while the system is running both N and N+1 to ensure both can interoperate with each other, but after all are N+1, its wasteful, since all the software is now capable of reading only from the new location.

So the procedure is something like this maybe:
 1. online upgrade schema to N compatible schema (expand).
 2. upgrade a node at a time to N+1. It sees compatible schema and uses migration compatible code.
 3. online upgrade schema to N+1 schema (contract), this finishes migration and deletes the old things
 4. controllers notice schema upgrade or are notified and can stop doing compatibility code.

Cluster's now at N+1. The performance hits affect the system for the length of time step 2 is running. With the spec proposal, this degraded mode lasts at least 6 months. With the alternate proposal, it will probably last only hours or less."}, {'account_id': 14250, 'date': '2015-12-01 18:01:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Kevin

I understand the performance hit, although in a case that a column changes type it would still be just one insert or update.

What I'm saying is that currently, there is no way (or no straightforward way) to update an SQLAlchemy model without changing code, thus at least two releases are needed:
 * first new release adds a second column and migrates the data
 * the second release stops using the old column

In the second release, if expand/contract is implemented, we can drop the column in the contract phase. Currently in keystone, we would have to wait for the third release, and do it in the normal schema migration script which is run before starting new code.

Maybe if we keep two versions of SQLAlchemy models, and introduce an abstraction layer in between, we could replace the model, when a migration is complete... The state of the migration can be saved in the config file and reloaded without stopping the service (this is now supported by oslo)."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-12-01 22:59:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

We currently have an issue where we'd like to start putting the token audit_id in the revocation list. In order to make this change, I'd like to add a column to the token table with the token audit ID. The token audit ID is currently in the "extra" column which is a blob and getting the audit id from there is a performance problem. Without online schema migration we'd just add the column with default NULL, copy the data, then alter the column to disallow NULLs.

With online schema migration,

a) new migration adds the column and copies the audit ids (can't make the column nullable since old keystone doesn't know about it).

b) the new code needs to support audit_id is null by reading the token extra data if it's not present. The new code updates the rows with NULL audit_id when it sees them so they're not NULL anymore.

c) in the next release new migration removes nullable from audit_id

This is OK but it's going to be hard to test and enforce in all cases. Just adding a test for not dropping the columns seems inadequate.'}, {'account_id': 14250, 'date': '2015-12-02 14:46:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Brant

I'm planning to work on adding a grenade (or multi-node grenade) job which would at least check running tempest jobs on the old code, with updated schema and then run tempest again with the new version. I'm sure this would catch more issues and can be refined after it is integrated into keystone CI."}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-12-02 20:24:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Grzegorz Grasza:

Ah, I understand about the sqlalchemy model issue. Leaving columns/tables around that aren't used for a cycle is just fine. Its the migration code constantly running to cover the (N & N+1) case even when the cluster's all (N+1) that I'm worried about as an OP. If that were covered more explicitly in the spec, that would be good enough for me I think."}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2015-12-03 07:05:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2

At the last keystone meeting [0], this spec was well supported by the core team and received no negative votes.

There does however seem to be issues around the benefits that will be gained. The spec proposes tests, functional and upgrade. But does not cover the impact on developer time. Operator desire is another issue.

I don't mind approving this for mitaka, but i'd like to hear a bit more feedback from the folks we are trying to help before approving.

[0] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/keystone/2015/keystone.2015-12-01-18.01.html"}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2015-12-03 07:17:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9500, 'date': '2015-12-03 19:37:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

this is going to be super useful for us. It significantly reduces the risk and simplifies the machinations of an upgrade.'}, {'account_id': 14250, 'date': '2015-12-07 14:17:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)

Hi,
 after some time for thought, I think I have a better idea on how to approach the performance and security concerns (voiced above) than what we came up with after the IRC discussion last Tuesday [1].

My proposal is to skip writing the data migration code.

The unit test will stay as-is, and will still block incompatible schema changes. The end result would be, that running two adjacent versions would not immediately throw schema related errors. This way, the operator will have more options on how to do the upgrade, (s)he could:

1. Upgrade the service with less downtime, by performing some of the migrations before stopping the old release
2. After looking at the release notes or/and the schema migration scripts, the operator could implemented DB triggers to migrate the data online
3. An operator may make a conscious decision to do a rolling-upgrade without any modifications, taking into account his specific use-case and user stories put forward by the community.

I will also propose a backlog spec for "Online data migration" and we could discuss the performance and security issues there.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-operators/2015-December/009047.html'}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2015-12-07 14:52:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
fix metadata test

Amazon changes key owner for imported keys.
So test should check key only without onwer.

Change-Id: I491b6ac1de08df28a85944b5b00347659c847136

commit_message:
Remove invalid TODO in extensions

There are TODO notes asking for a description in
the following extensions: ec2, s3, user_crud and
endpoint_filter. However, the descriptions
already exist.

This change remove those notes.

Change-Id: I1d2c42b471030d61b6bb1be5d240253eb00767f6

Improve comments in test_catalog

This patch is a continuation from;
I59c4478a30f22f103b1f498f566b7f955f9c8848

- Fix some grammar nits

- Replace v2 to v2.0

Co-Authored-By: Tony Wang <wwwjfy@gmail.com>

Hi Priti,

the supported filter is on project ID. There is no filter on project name for list_role_assignments. Available filters are listed on [1].

I just rechecked with Henry Nash in the IRC channel and, the point is that we don't check multiple policy rule for one API. Thus listing role assignments already works. See our current rule [2].

If horizon, or other client is doing a GET project before listing role assignments, that's another thing.

I suggest you to make it clear you are addressing only GET project API, and the policy changes here have nothing to do with list role assignments, from a server point of view.

Perhaps "Fix for GET project by project admin" should be the right way to go with this patch.

You could submit the tests for list role assignments in a separate change.

[1] http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-identity-v3.html#listRoleAssignments
[2] https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/85b8158/etc/policy.v3cloudsample.json#L94'}, {'account_id': 17860, 'date': '2015-12-06 20:58:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

[{'created': '2015-11-23 19:59:59.000000000', 'message': 'Fix for listing role assignments by project admin

Project admin fails to list role assignments for his project with
Project Scoped Token.
The issue is project admin in default policy file
(policy.v3cloudsample.json) does not have access to get details
of his project. Due to this, keystone assumes that the project
does not exist, and tries to get the project listing which again
fails.
This change updates the default policy file to let project
administrators to retrieve their own project details.

Change-Id: I60995db12a90c8ce6090099dee79ed1e5ee5caed
Closes-Bug: 1418702

commit_message:
Fix for GET project by project admin

The issue is project admin in default policy file
(policy.v3cloudsample.json) does not have access to get details
of his project.

This change updates the default policy file to let project
administrators to retrieve their own project details.

Change-Id: I60995db12a90c8ce6090099dee79ed1e5ee5caed
Closes-Bug: 1418702

commit_message:
Update swift port to match in puppet-tripleo

Previously, the port used for swift when TLS is enabled was found to be
conflicting in puppet-tripleo, so it was updated to avoid this
conflict. But that change needs to be reflected here too, as it will
point to an incorrect port otherwise.

Change-Id: Iad40a0b097a09a43cddc4f1a2637a9452c029414

commit_message:
Replace full-width quotes with half-width quotes

The comment in tox.ini line 36 use full-width quotes between hashtag(#).
I think should replace them with half-width quotes.

Change-Id: I38b09f5de04add396deb969272657f765aece716
Closes-Bug: #1523795

Support neutron QoSPolicy resource plugin

Provide some resources to support Neutron QoS capability.
This patch add OS::Neutron::QoSPolicy resource plugin.

Blueprint: support-neutron-qos

(1 comment)

It is just a draft. More discussion will be appreciated.'}, {'account_id': 9981, 'date': '2015-11-17 14:22:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

This looks like a good start and fills an important gap.

One key question to me: who is the audience for this documentation?

To me, the document currently blends how to report a bug, and how to triage a bug. If the audience for this document is mostly OpenStack consumers, I'd suggest more focus on how to report a bug (no need to describe toolchain issues, for example), and maybe more info on what exactly to include in a bug report.

If this is for developers or consumers, I'd think the reporting of bugs should be to openstack-i18n. Using language team tracking mechanisms seems appropriate only for translators to me.

OTOH if this is for OpenStack translators including information on how to triage problems is helpful."}, {'account_id': 17765, 'date': '2015-11-17 18:52:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I see also this hen/egg problem. If you want to report bugs in translation you have to translate the bug tracking tool. If the audience of the document are Openstack Community we are fine (developer, translation team). For consumer a language-spezific disclaimer at the end of documentation could be helpful, where is explained how to deal with bugs.'}, {'account_id': 14482, 'date': '2015-11-18 02:39:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(4 comments)

Please see my comments.

My suggestion is to tell that Launchpad is our best and preferred tool to receive bugs, but we are welcome to receive bugs through directly for translators and other ways via i18n mailing list or IRC conversation.

By the day, it seems that my English expression needs to be more improved.. Please help it :)'}, {'account_id': 14482, 'date': '2015-11-18 02:43:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

By the day -> By the way.. :)'}, {'account_id': 3108, 'date': '2015-11-18 03:22:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

Thank you for taking this initiative. The document will be very valuable. I also appreciated the comments the reviewers made. I have some points:
1. I don't like complicated ways. Use a simple and single (if possible) way to report translation contents related bugs. I18n team members could trial and classify those bugs. That could be a kind of meaningful works for I18n core team members.
2. Organize the document from the perspective of report roles: users, translators, tool users, and etc. ( I don't know if there are some kinds of i18n bugs a openstack developer could report. If there are, openstack developers should be added.)"}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-18 16:47:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Thanks for your all feedback! More input would be appreciated. I would like to post a updated version next week.'}, {'account_id': 14482, 'date': '2015-11-19 11:43:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(4 comments)

I also want to add more ideas in this important article!

I added my idea on 'reporting bugs' and included my comments for minor English correction :)"}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-23 12:08:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The discussion happened in the I18n team meeting. The log is

commit_message:
Destroy slaves in tests for IBP

Destroy slaves instead of graceful power off in test
for repeatable provisioning in order to avoid SSH session
hang.

Change-Id: I010a78adfff75fb0621354f1225342dcd1a334d0
Closes-bug: #1523601

commit_message:
Separate unit tests from fullstack tests

With this patch the tox command only runs the unit tests
at the ./kuryr/tests/unit lib.
Another test job is added for fullstack which is meant to be
run only with a working devstack setup and will run
at the gate with tempest.
You can run the tests there for debugging with 'tox -e fullstack'

implements blueprint: fullstack-testing

Change-Id: Ia646b3f1a2b25f0a7fd4d01ed72ea1b51bb3b21c

commit_message:
Remove version from setup.cfg

Per [1] and [2] we now want to use the git repository
for knowing the version instead of modifying the setup.cfg file.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/080692.html
[2] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-December/081431.html

Change-Id: Id45f5d62aae35dfb77afee265f803a02f9e9e50d

commit_message:
pyudev exception has changed for from_device_file

Now pyudev raises DeviceNotFoundByFileError which does not inherit
from EnvironmentError, so our 'except' block in hardware.py no longer
catch the exception. It broke unit tests, but it can also potentially
break the deploy.

This patch updates hardware.py to catch both old a new exceptions.

Change-Id: Iaefd6089f6f766a241054d8e132b2f3098c8130d
Closes-Bug: #1522756

[{'created': '2015-12-04 11:14:58.000000000', 'message': 'Make gate-swift-python34 voting and add gate job

After a long work which probably took one year or longer, the
python34 check job of Swift now pass since the change
I79f47fff6ec1adff214ca435f0d95aaf1ffd68f9.

Well, only a very simple unit test is currently run on Python 3, but
it's the first important milestone of the overall plan to port Swift
to Python 3:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/078058.html

To avoid reintroducing code incompatible (or dependencies
incompatible) with Python 3 in the code tested by "tox -e py34", we
must now make gate-swift-python34 voting. To be clear, this change
doesn't force developers to make *all new changes* compatible with
Python 3 immediatly. No. Only new changes touching the code tested by
"tox -e py34" must be compatible with Python 3, it's a smooth
transition.

This change also adds gate-swift-python34 as a gate job, by reusing
the python3-jobs template.

The liberty branch of Swift is completly broken on Python 3:
dependencies cannot be installed, the code is not compatible with
Python 3, etc. So this change also removes gate-swift-python34 on
Liberty to stop wasting resources of the openstack-infra. Let's focus
on the master branch for Mitaka.

Change-Id: If5664af152f7fa8929ee42d549641f9f7ed29841
'}]
commit_message:
Make gate-swift-python34 voting and add gate job

After a long work which probably took one year or longer, the
python34 check job of Swift now pass since the change
I79f47fff6ec1adff214ca435f0d95aaf1ffd68f9.

Well, only a very simple unit test is currently run on Python 3, but
it's the first important milestone of the overall plan to port Swift
to Python 3:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/078058.html

To avoid reintroducing code incompatible (or dependencies
incompatible) with Python 3 in the code tested by "tox -e py34", we
must now make gate-swift-python34 voting. To be clear, this change
doesn't force developers to make *all new changes* compatible with
Python 3 immediatly. No. Only new changes touching the code tested by
"tox -e py34" must be compatible with Python 3, it's a smooth
transition.

This change also adds gate-swift-python34 as a gate job, by reusing
the python3-jobs template.

The liberty branch of Swift is completly broken on Python 3:
dependencies cannot be installed, the code is not compatible with
Python 3, etc. So this change also removes gate-swift-python34 on
Liberty to stop wasting resources of the openstack-infra. Let's focus
on the master branch for Mitaka.

Change-Id: If5664af152f7fa8929ee42d549641f9f7ed29841

commit_message:
Keystonemiddleware shouldn't list options of other lib

If an application have already registered options
of keystoneauth and then use list_auth_token_opts()
to register the keystonemiddleware options it got
DuplicatedOption Exception from oslo.config.

This change fixes that.

Change-Id: Iada0fa510c051f55115d98d94358dac66988ecad
Closes-bug: #1522014

commit_message:
Seperate unit and fullstack testing in dragonflow

Dragonflow tox command now only runs tests
inside /dragonflow/tests/unit .
This patch also introduce another test job that will
be used for gate tempest testing called 'fullstack'.
You can debug tests written there using
'tox -e fullstack'
Tests in this lib assume a working devstack installation
with dragonflow exists.

Change-Id: I3089f9caab9062fee7f60bbcd5c17c72071c62ac

commit_message:
tox: rm all pyc before doing unit test

Delete python bytecode before every test run.
Because python creates pyc files during tox runs, certain
changes in the tree, like deletes of files, or switching
branches, can create spurious errors.

Closes-Bug: #1368661
Change-Id: If31ffc245ade9f62b61f99246e59208208ed4fb1

commit_message:
Adding support for Manila-based shares in Sahara

The Sahara data processing service now supports manila
shares as a location for job binaries.  Also adding a unit
test for creation of manila-based job binaries.

Change-Id: I6599aca1baabe9875f6ac3ed847cb5030f0e5bb7
Implements: bp add-manila-binary-store

Different ETCD installation

Install ETCD as a service leveraging calico repository.
This is done in order to pass gate tests, this installation
must be later done using our own repos.

commit_message:
Consume LBaaS v2 plugin queue in RPC workers

This patch adds all RPC workers to consumers of LBaaS v2 plugin
queue.
This is important for DVR-enabled deployments with hundreds
of agents.

Change-Id: Iaec2f623cbbba99d17dc15802ed70603db37e0fb
Related-Bug: #1498844

commit_message:
Increase the heat stack wait time out

This fix handles the usecase where Tacker falsely sets the VNF to
ERROR state after waiting for 50 seconds even though the actual
stack is succesfully completed whose creation time is greater than
50 seconds.

The current default wait time out of 50 seconds is bumped up to
300 seconds as a fair timeout, keeping the memory/cpu constrained
vms/systems in consideration.

Closes-Bug: #1521323
Change-Id: Ied1d904cc0dac2df91dee856100baeb988d65676

commit_message:
Fix AttributeError raised from output of nova host-list

Currently, calling host-list command gets AttributeError: host.
This patch is to use self.to_dict() command instead of self.host, 
to send the full host details to caller.

Change-Id: Ifd4d8d659f6a9e9c6e384a7032faf32114481678
Closes-Bug:#1513787

commit_message:
Move import for netifaces

Since netifaces is used in only one spot and is something
that is rarely needed (hence optional as extras in setup.cfg)
We should import it only if needed. This should have been
taken care of as part of change id. but got missed.
If3430364e49c1c0b1d9f4937bb67900380662728

Change-Id: Ie79db6720e88a250e26e79b37e717bd82ec89736

Trival: Remove 'MANIFEST.in'

Everything in this file is automatically generated by pbr. There
appears to be no good reason to keep it around.
More details please see:
https://github.com/openstack-dev/pbr/blob/master/pbr/packaging.py#L384

commit_message:
Match locale dir to the current infra script

At now, the infra scripts which handles translation expect
that locale files (PO/POT) are placed at <repo_name>. [1]
It is confusing to setup a locale directory different from
the path expected by the infra script.

[1] See setup_project in jenkins/scripts/common_translation_update.sh
in the project-config repo.

Change-Id: Idbaa789d3f28325a5028ec2b167b4d2bed4e05cf

commit_message:
(WIP)Add user/project information to audit events

The current audit event generated from Keystonemiddleware
does not pass in user/project information as part of the
event like it used to for pycadf. This change explicitly
passes on this information so that ceilometer events finally
pick this information up as an Event Trait

Partially Closes-Bug: 1461767

Change-Id: Ic997fa876e463bb003f8f9d8e3395d94421989ca

commit_message:
docs: add the scheduler evolution plans

The scheduler evolution has been a priority for both kilo and liberty.
This document attempts to describe the general direction of that effort.

The goal for this work is to make it easier for others to help with this
effort, and make sure we agree the current direction.

Change-Id: I8746362b6a596690de21de34599462a6e27a92da

commit_message:
Fix the link to updateExtraRoutes

The commit Ib8c965cef7d9e49ef7d03cbb0234f15826345cf5 didn't change
one link to updateExtraRoutes, then we cannot open the link now on
the api-site. This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I8fbae43c0efa7f1e31965a518fba1880986f2437
Closes-Bug: #1523359

commit_message:
Fix create flavor ref link

During rebase of I8350034bac7bc6ce794bf711f7fb5d5b9510ae55, create flavor link
was not updated in method ref.
Due to that, create flavor was missing in compute api ref doc.

This patch fixes this issue.

Closes-Bug: #1522293

Change-Id: I320175bf5ca123b0ac548d2bd8c981b2189cf75e

commit_message:
Add bug report project definition feature

Some teams use openstackdocstheme which have each launchpad project.
To report a bug to the appropriate project directly,
enable each project to define the bug report project.

To define it, add the html_context at Sphinx conf.py.
For example:
  html_context = {"bug_project": 'openstack-training-guides', ...}

Change-Id: I75d3c068305ad475ba75649e6185741dc511668b

commit_message:
[diff_branches] Projects can be passed as arguments

The list of projects being worked on by the script was hardcoded. This
patch adds the possibility to pass the list of projects to work on as
arguments on the command line.

Remove a project-list-related special case for trove on havana.

Change-Id: I7eb282fe9050a9c9367ee1ad72d9adbf6db29063

Because python creates pyc/pyo files during tox runs, certain
changes in the tree, like deletes of files, or switching

'}]
commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run

Because python creates pyc/pyo files during tox runs, certain
changes in the tree, like deletes of files, or switching
branches, can create spurious errors.

This patch removes these unrequired files when tox
starts execution, along with the __pycache__ folder for
py3* compilation.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I2ab9ffe1d1665bd86cc871075b5652da5f05d069
Closes-Bug: #1368661

commit_message:
Fix db error when running python34 Unit tests

If tests for py27 is executed before py34 tests, then
there is a chance that py34 related tests may fail.The following
patch fixes it.

Ref: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:merged++topic:bug/1489059,n,z

TrivialFix

Change-Id: Ie395ff323f52f81ad4f7a6ab78c85c71873fbe87
Closes-bug: #1489059

commit_message:
Automatically generate neutron FWaaS configuration files

This adds a new tox environment, genconfig, which generates sample
neutron FWaaS configuration file using oslo-config-generator.

Partially-Implements: blueprint autogen-neutron-conf-file

Change-Id: I8e9113dfb88e5290f6eedd012d1a52fc35c3c88c
Partial-bug: #1199963

commit_message:
Lower l2pop "isn't bound to any segement" log to debug

Per the discussion in bug 1362242, the log statement doesn't
appear to be associated with anything bad happening. Therefore,
this patch lowers the log level from WARNING to DEBUG to avoid
polluting operator's logs.

Change-Id: I55b6d1d30ed2ed55659c9a6809531cfcbc57f17c
Signed-off-by: Ryan Moats <rmoats@us.ibm.com>
Closes-Bug: 1362242
(cherry picked from commit eb09ebc88cd8eb57acdeb39a81674ca7b7a85c5f)

+1 on what Brian said, thanks Diana and Rob.   This is really awesome'}, {'account_id': 11798, 'date': '2015-12-07 14:20:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-12-07 18:16:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 31:

I did a comparison of what we have vs what is on the bootstrap page: http://getbootstrap.com/components/#wells Here are some of my thoughts while looking at the preview page.

1. The links to the various components at the top of the page look awkward and out of place. Why not have it like the bootstrap page?

2. Layout of the components could use some work and description. For example, if I don't compare it to the bootstrap page I may not know what a well is. Seems like bootstrap displays the snippet underneath rather than clicking on </>. I think this is cleaner, but not a deal breaker for me.

3. Finally, I think the concept is really nice. We can definitely extend this to include our own custom angular directives. But I do think there is one piece of glue missing - the ability to change themes on the fly. It's not really a theme review page unless you can do this.

For me, the blueprint should outline a plan on how to swap themes on the fly, that is currently the missing piece that would make this patch shine. It doesn't even have to be implemented. If we have a plan, I can throw my weight behind it and give it my full support."}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-12-07 18:16:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-12-07 19:35:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31:

Thai, I think you're misinterpreting the point of this page. Its not meant to be a copy of the bootstrap docs. It's just an example list with a simple nav of "these are default bootstrap components, and this is what your current theme is and how it looks". The on the fly switching will be a separate patch, but for now I think this has value in showing what your current theme looks like. It's fairly trivial to change settings and collectstatic.'}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-12-07 19:41:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 31: Code-Review+1

Thai,

Thanks for the comments.

#1: Its meant to recreate the experience shows on Bootswatch's pages.  We can change the experience if its really needed, but I think this is fine as an initial version.

#2: Its not the purpose of the preview page to educate the Brander on what a well is ... or anything else. I've found the simple layout very useful in recent branding efforts. Its supposed to represent a very very quick overview of all of the Bootstrap components visually, that's why you need to click to get the mark up to recreate.  We want the preview to be as small and concise as possible.

#3 - On the fly themes is already in the works and is part of another blueprint:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/horizon-dynamic-theme


The getbootstrap page is not meant to show case a theme, it has way more context than what we need to provide."}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-12-07 20:01:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 31: Code-Review+2

The biggest irk for me was a details on swapping themes easily on the front-end, seems like it will get address in a different blueprint. I still feel like navigation and layout can us some work, but I won't hold the patch up since this is the initial run through."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-12-07 23:38:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 31: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

(1 comment)

This is a developer page and intended to help people building themes to see how things look. I don't think we need to bikeshed over this when it can start helping people now. I think getting it in is valuable and we can improve from there. Here are a couple tiny notes for future consideration:

I like that there is a TOC at the top. Maybe it can be improved, but nice to have.

Why is Navbar the first thing? It seems like something very few people will ever use.  Why isn't it grouped with Navs?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-07 23:38:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-12-07 23:39:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31:

BTW, the second I hit "publish comments" I immediately realized that seeing the navbar at the top is one of the first things people doing simple theming may want to see... so I understand why you put it there.'}, {'account_id': 17130, 'date': '2015-12-08 03:55:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-08 05:09:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31: Verified+2

commit_message:
Add Developer Dashboard + Bootstrap Theme Preview

Themers need an easy way to see how customizations in
the new themeing mechanism will affect known bootstrap
elements.

While DEBUG is True, the developer dashboard will be present in the
Horizon nav sidebar. This currently displays the Bootstrap Theme Preview
page, and will also be used for Angular widget demos etc in the future.

Documentation on SCSS and the preview page are being provided in a
separate patch to coordinate with the theming work
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1514869)

Note: The SECRET_KEY block in settings.py is moved before the enabled
files setup, so that importing settings in the enabled file doesn't
cause errors.

Co-Authored-By: Diana Whitten <hurgleburgler@gmail.com>

Implements: blueprint bootstrap-theme-preview
Change-Id: I44bc52d4dcfbbdc60a27879e638d78c4b508b2e9

commit_message:
Support Linux-IO in addition to tgtd

The iSCSI extension now tries to use Linux-IO first (via rtslib)
and falls back to tgtd if Linux-IO can't be used (e.g. in the CoreOS-based
image which uses containers).

Change-Id: I9cc7a30d9c93c445a66d183146e9260c2b096d33
Closes-Bug: #1504562

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more

commit_message:
Add support for configuring rgw using civetweb

Added parameters to rgw.pp and profile.pp to support the configuration
of radosgw using civetweb

Fixed a typo and now passes puppet-list --no-autoloader_layout-check --no-80chars-check

Change-Id: I755d948da6af7c0ed1b194243533d74b5fc1f696
Signed-off-by: Keith Schincke <keith.schincke@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Make desired_capacity default to min_size if min_size specified

This patch makes desired_capacity default to min_size if min_zize
specified but desired_capacity not when creating cluster, it would
be more friendly to user.

Change-Id: Ie498f128bbd410d116abdf759d65adec0488dcec

commit_message:
Revert to use keystone v2 based OSC

Reverting back to use keystone v2 based openstackclient command because
folks are getting confused about the command differences. The previous
'fix' doesn't work if without additional options.

Change-Id: I8a3cc69079d969f3ac13d80c0b02ee89bede071d

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: I4d4c200e733568d33116728e19377575b92331ca

subject: Remove qpid messaging support

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: Ib18cb5b49195371704ae245d68318a870235b724

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: I8a0c9293e943621fd556083e4aed413cb2b1f63c

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: Ic604be82fd3ca1cd595de1f63f151b74502714f2

commit_message:
VMware: Unit test refactoring (image to vol - 2/2)

There are cases where a single test tests multiple methods. This
patch refactors the unit tests for the following methods in the
vmdk module to fix this issue:
   * _create_virtual_disk_from_preallocated_image
   * _create_virtual_disk_from_sparse_image
   * _fetch_stream_optimized_image

There will be follow-up patches to fix the remaining unit tests.

Change-Id: I6b738f08b89e518c78a26a934fead42cc86e0c24
Depends-On: Icd2c3d506647b7b9405d83612433fea735d13cc9

Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: Ifa421b20ba218b5bb3d2041687cb3d843924f94e

commit_message:
Use 3 decimals on timestamp calculation

Simplify timestamp_to_iso_millis_delta function
because python api is using 3 decimals now.
Added end_time on query params to make sure the
tests can pass.

Change-Id: I1e327bb03740e11792481d74b448668e99db65a7

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: I11ea3f58dc48b12dd6a536c3d56e57b7c48e6810

subject: Remove qpid messaging support

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: I5a702aacf77956a6c616fd98d2f942654548f00d

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: I46f3681963b4a365f2c5cdd7f5f6168adb751551

commit_message:
Add OVS_OF_INTERFACE variable

Add OVS_OF_INTERFACE as variable to switch a mode of ovs mechanism driver.
OVS_OF_INTERFACE takes a value of 'ovs-ofctl' or 'native'.

Change-Id: I92cc487e400c789991eeca4a95237b75a251a281

commit_message:
Avoid duplicate client resource

python-openstackclient is used by a few other classes, so switch to
ensure_resource to avoid duplicate package declarations.

Partial-Bug: #1523643

Change-Id: I437b266344cf6ace683379c1999fc08fbdee756c

commit_message:
VMware: Replace mox with mock

This patch replaces usages of mox with mock in the VMDK driver unit tests.
It also refactors the unit tests for copy_volume_to_image so that those
tests test only a single method.

Closes-Bug: #1261097
Change-Id: I50925a3aed1df12a283e9ec20f2bc2add1aad162

commit_message:
Make date window for job pages longer for periodic jobs

Periodic jobs by their nature run far less frequently than pre-merge
ci jobs. As such the graphs showing the per job statistics aren't really
meaningful when looking at a single day. This commit makes the window
as big as the other pages when being run for a periodic job. The window
is still kept small for other jobs because of performance reasons.

Eventually we want to have all the graphs have a date window slider to
make the generated results as big or as small as required. This will
likely be made obsolete when this is implemented. But, in the meantime
lets make things at least moderately useful.

Change-Id: Icb32a8784ef70b2b7ff2e95f7aa12371b7dbaac1

commit_message:
Bump oslo.service version to 1.0.0

Main changes in versions 0.13.0 and 1.0.0:
    * Default value of graceful_shutdown_timeout option is set
      to 60sec
    * Support for SSL protocol and cipher controls - new config
      options
    * Add functionality for creating Unix domain WSGI servers

Change-Id: I1771c81f7d4f5102d1f319049fbba031a02f43c0

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-02 17:55:54.000000000', 'message': 'Do not allow name lookups on RBAC policies

RBAC policies have no name field so the name query to
the server was always returning all entries since the
name filter was ignored.

This corrects the behavior by disabling the name lookup
for RBAC policies.

Change-Id: I6c5afa05cefb1709e9667a1aaf20105c707dc95c
Closes-Bug: #1517818
(cherry picked from commit 529d3f5a3c8d71df23d795275f01ec4a4aca994b)
'}]
commit_message:
Do not allow name lookups on RBAC policies

RBAC policies have no name field so the name query to
the server was always returning all entries since the
name filter was ignored.

This corrects the behavior by disabling the name lookup
for RBAC policies.

Change-Id: I6c5afa05cefb1709e9667a1aaf20105c707dc95c
Closes-Bug: #1517818
(cherry picked from commit 529d3f5a3c8d71df23d795275f01ec4a4aca994b)

commit_message:
Ensure to decode bytes or fail

The commit fcf289797c063088f9003359dfd1c7d4f41ed5ef introduces the
pattern:

  if isinstance(line, bytes):
    try:
      line = line.decode(encoding='utf-8')
    except UnicodeError:
      pass
  # concat line with a string

which is not working in PY3K if an UnicodeError is raised because line
is not decoded and concatened to a string.

This change delegates decoding to safe_decode[1] which returns a text
object or raises an error.

[1] oslo_utils.encodeutils

Closes-Bug: #1503415
Related-Bug: #1499004
Change-Id: I16b8013f33aa3efad65be8040d3210120e047bbd
(cherry picked from commit 88eb5845b77fa06a12c096706093329f82dba54c)

commit_message:
Fix db error when running python34 Unit tests

If tests for py27 is executed before py34 tests, then
there is a chance that py34 related tests may fail.
The following patch fixes it.

Ref: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:merged++topic:bug/1489059,n,z

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I99dd7a67829bbf9115e011373ce43d8e893e5c66
Closes-bug: #1489059

commit_message:
Update tosca-parser minimum version to 0.3.0

Due to recent changes to tosca-parser that include modified
error handling and reformatting error messages projects that
use them (i.e., heat-translator) need to make sure they run
against the version 0.3.0 or higher of tosca-parser.

Change-Id: I968181acca8903b9c21773b1c1e93f31753e0ba0

[{'created': '2015-12-06 23:16:31.000000000', 'message': 'Bump the keystonemiddleware minimum

Move keystonemiddleware minimum to 4.0.0 as this now includes the
correct mock fixture for testing keystonemiddleware which will avoid
the need to mock/patch the internal interfaces in a way that could
break consuming projects.

Change-Id: If617556aa0b4e657f1bf95d4a73f7b9abdd34f90
'}]
commit_message:
Bump the keystonemiddleware minimum

Move keystonemiddleware minimum to 4.0.0 as this now includes the
correct mock fixture for testing keystonemiddleware which will avoid
the need to mock/patch the internal interfaces in a way that could
break consuming projects.

Change-Id: If617556aa0b4e657f1bf95d4a73f7b9abdd34f90

commit_message:
Add funcsigs into global-requirements.txt

This library will be useful for oslo.utils and its consumers
so that they can correctly examine function signatures across
the python versions that the community supports.

Is the library actively maintained?

  Not especially, lifeless and I are working on taking over
  ownership, this should be happening very soon as it appears
  the author is not responsive to emails or other.

Is the library good code?

  I have seen worse.

Is the library python 3 compatible?

  The main purpose of this library is to be a backport of
  PEP 362 so on python 3 it isn't really needed in the first
  place.

Is the library license compatible?

  Yes.

Is the library already packaged in the distros we target?

  It appears to be packaged in ubuntu latest, fedora appears
  to have a package that may not be distributed yet as well.

Is the function of this library already covered by other
libraries in global-requirements.txt?

  Nope

Change-Id: I1aa0054089ca57fc2d68779f4ee133a9750fec2a

commit_message:
Add ipaddress to global-requirements.txt

Port of the 3.3+ ipaddress module to 2.6, 2.7, 3.2

- Is the library actively maintained?

  Yes. See the recent commit history at:
  https://github.com/phihag/ipaddress/commits/master

- Is the library good code?

  Yes, given it's a port of a Python 3.3 module.

- Is the library python 3 compatible?

  Yes.

- Is the library license compatible?

  The license is Python Software Foundation License Version 2:
  https://github.com/phihag/ipaddress/blob/master/LICENSE

- Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu
  latest / Fedora latest)?

  Yes, it's packaged for Ubuntu, Fedora, CentOS.

- Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries
  in ``global-requirements.txt``?

  Not that I'm aware of.

Change-Id: Ide4c15da4f894eb41f8728b8f0e2620bedf89528

commit_message:
keyring older then 5.5.1 may print warning

keyring older 5.5.1 can print unexpected warnings
when used with GnomeKeyring.

Bumping the required keyring version to 5.5.1,
this is the fixing commit:
https://github.com/jaraco/keyring/commit/47a51f8da1e0d3fa946327fb9fba1d3ebd4ff275

Closes-Bug: #1517907

external-ids:iface-id=$port_name external-ids:iface-status=active \

TOKEN_ID=<keystone token (can be retrieved with 'keystone token-get')>
curl -g -i -X POST http://172.16.75.129:9696/v2.0/ports.json -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN_ID" -d '{"port": {"network_id": "fdc49002-e18a-462f-860f-437c86402469", "binding:profile": {"local_link_information": [{"switch_info": "HOSTNAMEOFCOMPUTE", "port_id": "mtlTEST"}]}, "binding:vnic_type": "baremetal", "admin_state_up": true, "binding:host_id": "HOSTNAMEOFCOMPUTE"}}'

commit_message:
[WIP]: 'baremetal' support for OVS agent

This patch allows ports to be attached to OVS and have them
bound to the correct network based on the local_link_information
on baremetal ports.

The prefix of the port must be 'mtl' for now (to avoid excessive
db lookups on other ports).

To add a port to OVS:

port_name=mtlTEST
port_mac=00:11:22:33:44:55
sudo ovs-vsctl --timeout=120 -- --if-exists del-port $port_name -- \
add-port br-int $port_name -- set Interface $port_name \
external-ids:iface-id=$port_name external-ids:iface-status=active \
external-ids:attached-mac=$port_mac type=internal

Add the port on the Neutron side:

TOKEN_ID=$(keystone token-get | grep ' id ' | awk '{ print $4 }')
NEUTRON_URL=http://172.16.75.129:9696
curl -g -i -X POST $NEUTRON_URL/v2.0/ports.json -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN_ID" -d '{"port": {"network_id": "fdc49002-e18a-462f-860f-437c86402469", "binding:profile": {"local_link_information": [{"switch_id": "'$(hostname)'", "port_id": "mtlTEST"}]}, "binding:vnic_type": "baremetal", "admin_state_up": true, "binding:host_id": "'$(hostname)'"}}'

Change-Id: I3ae4111757158482dda69302d40a66b3c8468b5f

commit_message:
Remove unused vxlan_group option from ML2

The vxlan_group option was brought into ML2 in commit
81e87775c8ab56c4b4c7b5048041caef7670bc9d; however, it
was never actually used for anything.

This option isn't to be confused with the option by the
same name used by the Linux bridge agent, which is actually
used.[1]

1. https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/e3a531a1fa681d7a4aa169b9420f22f068691cbd/neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/linuxbridge/agent/common/config.py#L34-L42

DocImpact: remove any references to 'vxlan_group' in the
context of ML2 configuration options. The only 'vxlan_group'
references should be for Linux Bridge agent configuration.

Closes-Bug: #1523614
Change-Id: I2b7ca50dc0620452d12406de3d16eb4cddaf0084

commit_message:
Depend on oslo.utils[netifaces]

We import netutils from oslo.utils, which requires netifaces to be
imported. However, netifaces moved to an extra in oslo.utils here:
https://github.com/openstack/oslo.utils/commit/2abbe1c3b19490f570c29502cd56ec92daf4ca45
Depend on this extras package.

Change-Id: I09b71241420d6f82c9f46de7b4c58a9e1b04f4b1
Related-Bug: #1523706

commit_message:
Add openssh-server package-install to local-config

Since we are modifing SSH keys, it should be safe to assume
openssh-server should be installed too.

Change-Id: I17ff05642bb2f0868d4c17819cd91b179068399a
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fix policy json file to delete project checking

This patch fixes default JSON file used for policy checking. Policy
checking at this layer is not deemed useful from the community. It may
eventually go away. This also fixes some other issues introduced by
previous changes.

[{'created': '2015-12-07 08:40:53.000000000', 'message': "Remove 'tenant_id' from senlin API paths

This is an effort to remove the 'tenant_id' from API endpoints. With
most senlin objects now augmented with 'project_safe' queries, we don't
need this 'tenant_id' in the endpoint URIs now. It is suggested that all
OS projects do this change in future.

Project based checking at API layer is not well justified a reason to
have 'tenant_id'. In fact, the check is meaningless.

Change-Id: Ia99e56e7a2a45fcdd884c502e2c03b920fee6e1a
"}]
commit_message:
Remove 'tenant_id' from senlin API paths

This is an effort to remove the 'tenant_id' from API endpoints. With
most senlin objects now augmented with 'project_safe' queries, we don't
need this 'tenant_id' in the endpoint URIs now. It is suggested that all
OS projects do this change in future.

Project based checking at API layer is not well justified a reason to
have 'tenant_id'. In fact, the check is meaningless.

Change-Id: Ia99e56e7a2a45fcdd884c502e2c03b920fee6e1a

commit_message:
Autorequire mistral-common in mistral_config.

Updates the mistral_config type so that we autorequire
the mistral-common package. This fixes a slew of
configuration errors when trying to functionally
use this module without first installing the
mistral package.

Change-Id: I691637a533eb3fac89534a72cd65cb0373c4cd5b

commit_message:
Fix service setup script for new endpoints

We are removing 'tenant_id' from the senlin endpoints. This patch fixes
the setup script to make it: 1. work with latest service change; 2. work
with new changes to openstackclient.

Change-Id: I12a5b7acbe76370ceab3e79a807d91da22707d60

Much better version. Just a couple more points. I still object to the MFA language.'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2015-11-20 15:15:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I like the idea, but:

1) I am unsure on where operator would assign roles to a shadow users. My understanding is that whenever a federated user is logging in keystone is checking whether such user is already present in the shadow table. If it is, this means client was here in the past. If the entry is missing, we are creating it. Now, where are all those information about role assignments are coming from? The mapping? I doubt shadow users need to be propoulated cause this will basically reflect what we already have to day (using federation as a authN mechanism, where identity is local). 

2) What about backwards compatibility especially wrt old mapping rules, dynamic group membership etc? Shall we still support ephemeral users until we deprecate current mapping syntax and design? 

3) IMHO this spec should also mention what happens when a client wishes to defederate himself. Shall we disable all shadow users, or remove them from the table? I am opting for the latter. Think of public cloud providers who allows for quick on premise burssting from private cloud. Lots of clients will do this once or twice, probably for a short period of time. I am not sure a cloud provider will want to keep historical data and remember 'any user keystone has ever ever seen'."}, {'account_id': 18338, 'date': '2015-11-20 15:34:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 17860, 'date': '2015-11-25 18:12:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)

I agree with the inline comments from Guang and Marek. I also think the questions in last Marek's comment are important points that need to be clarified.

Other than that, this spec is pretty well written."}, {'account_id': 13478, 'date': '2015-11-26 10:07:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> I am not sure a cloud provider will want to keep historical data and remember 'any user keystone has ever ever seen'.

Why not? These federated users might come back once. They still technically exist and might want to come back later. 

Also, "defederating" a user would basically mean deleting one of his credentials, because SQL password, LDAP entry, X.509 certs are just means of AuthN.'}, {'account_id': 13478, 'date': '2015-11-26 10:10:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2015-11-26 10:17:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Boris, you are pulling my quotation out of the context. I was talking about a situation where client says 'ok, i no longer want to be your client'. In the normal case will the provider keep the data about the users or potentially delete it (maybe after some time hoping the client would return) in the longer term. And the same situation goes with shadow user. If somebody federates for one day, and the next defederates the ultimate policy should not be 'i will keep this identity forever'. As per specification, the identity mean should be constant (so, I will always get identitcal identity with each my authentication), so if i happen to come back one day and the entry will be missing keystone will create it once again."}, {'account_id': 13478, 'date': '2015-11-26 11:11:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Remove obsolete tenant parameter

The puppet-keystone module has removed the tenant parameter from the
keystone_user resource, so this update is needed for compatability.

Change-Id: Ib11cf074acee2429f81882139e3409138585e45c

commit_message:
Remove qpid messaging support

Qpid messaging driver is removed from Oslo.messaging [1]
Therefore, we cannot support it anymore.

[1] I4a9cba314c4a2f24307504fa7b5427424268b114

Change-Id: I9c4c04cbe4451380f67be067b5831d80fad48524

commit_message:
bump uppper constraints of pycadf and block 2.0.0

Due to a bug in version 2.0.0 of pycadf, we are excluding that
release. Newer versions, such as 2.0.1 are fine.

Related-Bug: 1521844

Change-Id: Ibc70ea0ec54d5edbd420cf7c82e6ae8312e887e5
Depends-On: I1df68d34e399a15f416b238d55d456b829208d9f

[{'created': '2015-11-18 13:41:51.000000000', 'message': "Support of PyMySQL driver for MySQL backend

Add ability to use python-pymysql library
as backend for MySQL connections.
Update acceptance tests to use pyMySQL.
Docs: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/PyMySQL_evaluation
The same implementation as it's done for keystone:

commit_message:
Support of PyMySQL driver for MySQL backend

Add ability to use python-pymysql library
as backend for MySQL connections.
Update acceptance tests to use pyMySQL.
Docs: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/PyMySQL_evaluation
The same implementation as it's done for keystone:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/242134/

Change-Id: If7a19e4c5492ea2464358144e706c62ee2c8a78a

(4 comments)

Mostly nits.'}, {'account_id': 9142, 'date': '2015-05-03 21:12:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I don't think it is worth it to change the way we currently work with roles this way.

i) Database: even if we unify the fields (as they will be the same), we won't save a lot of space;

ii) Role Assignments API: the actor and target ids are still not human-readable and will need to be set when assigning roles. Changing only the way we provide role ids won't make that difference.

I think what is worth it is to provide support in the clients (if we still dont) for accepting roles, actors and targets *names* (with domain info where needed).


----

In addition, for someone reading our role representation after this change would make sure we have a bad design on this API, since ids and names will be always the same:

{
    'id': 'project_admin',
    'name': 'project_admin'
}"}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-05-05 08:35:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I guess I am fundamentally against this one....since I believe we need domain specific roles....so unless we describe how we will also carry the domain part of the role, then I'm not sure how to support this."}, {'account_id': 8866, 'date': '2015-06-26 14:21:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Wrong Link to External Site Integrity life-cycle in Security Guide

A link to dm-verify under the section Node Hardening of Integrity
life-cycle is incorrect. The current link points to a a Google Code
page. The dm-verify project has been moved to Gitlab.

Change-Id: I8ef62f8a07cdb2c7bf6576985532220fc7faaec9
Closes-Bug: #1490049

commit_message:
Keystone_user fails with v2 openrc.

When /root/openrc is present and has a v2 auth_url, then keystone_user
resource will fail to check the password.

Change-Id: I4e7eb383800348ac55f11c68f45437c567507b79
Closes-Bug: #1522541

- gate-puppet-nova-puppet-lint http://logs.openstack.org/11/186511/1/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-lint/d08caab/ : SUCCESS in 2m 03s

- gate-puppet-nova-puppet-unit-3.3 http://logs.openstack.org/11/186511/1/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-unit-3.3/7461b2a/ : SUCCESS in 4m 27s
- gate-puppet-nova-puppet-unit-3.4 http://logs.openstack.org/11/186511/1/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-unit-3.4/a320993/ : SUCCESS in 6m 25s
