commit_message:
Add a note about ext modules remove to README

Sometimes, external modules cannot be fixed only
with -r key and should be removed and re-fetched.
This adds a note about such case to be covered
in the Noop tests readme.

Change-Id: Ie8f86e3567ffbfef6e69b7a73cc9c823141a0629
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-10-16 17:54:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi!  One question on the justification for this change.  What do you mean by improves compatibility?  I seem to be able to index into python3 unicode strings just fine?  I think readability and obviousness (vs error-proneness) is debatable/negligible/subjective.

Also:

$ python -m timeit '"asdf"[0] == "a"'
10000000 loops, best of 3: 0.0569 usec per loop
$ python -m timeit '"asdf".startswith("a")'
1000000 loops, best of 3: 0.233 usec per loop
$ python -m timeit '"asdf"[-1] == "f"'
10000000 loops, best of 3: 0.0572 usec per loop
$ python -m timeit '"asdf".endswith("f")'
1000000 loops, best of 3: 0.25 usec per loop

That's like what?  4x?  Probably doesn't matter, the real values are small.  But in addition to the work of reviewing all the changes for subtle issues that may be easy to miss unless someone is a) very familiar with the project or b) *very* familiar with python, AND making sure we have adequate test/branch coverage for the modules/lines being changed.  A healthy review should *ALSO* make sure to watch out for this sort of change in any critical run loop.

Peter & Peter, could either of you provide additional detail into the process you used for your review, or was it mostly just a spot check/lgtm vote?

Lastly, just fyi, I think a lot of maintainers eventually get burned out on *some* kinds of "trivial" cleanups that aim to make things more "proper"

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wf-BqAjZb8M&feature=youtu.be&t=510

That's in no way a knock on this change, just an open admission of personal failing that others may also share.

Feel free to reach out in #openstack-swift on freenode (or the mailing list, or launchpad low-hanging-fruit tag) if have any questions about some some easy fixes or helpful work or problematic areas of code that really *could* use some cleanup or better testing or whatever.  We're happy to help!'}, {'account_id': 18015, 'date': '2015-10-16 18:17:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I just used grep command to review missed lines.

Anyway it is recommended in pep8  https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/ to use functions instead of string slicing to check for prefixes or suffixes.

But if it ain't broke, don't fix it! :-)"}, {'account_id': 18820, 'date': '2015-10-16 19:09:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Mostly just a spot check for correctness - apologies if this wasn't sufficient.

The number of changes didn't seem *that* large and I assumed that test coverage would be adequate to catch anything. (In practice, this may not always be the case)

In any event, I would not be in favour of making this change if it would be a "slippery slope" to making further changes - I agree with the rule of "if it ain't broke, don't fix it" and pep8's general rule of "be consistent with surrounding code", so perhaps that's vote against it.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-10-16 20:29:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@peteL

yeah I agree with pep8 on string *slicing*

   x[:3] == 'bar'

isn't as good at describing what you mean as

    x.startswith('bar')

but if I'm trying to make the condition "the strings' first char is '_'" - it's got to be about the same to get there reading

    x[0] == '_'

... as it is to reword as "the string starts with the substring that is the single char '_'"

    x.startswith('_')

FWIW, I don't care for the use of `if len(x) == 0` instead of just `if len` (also recommended against in pep8) - and I'm not against the .startswith cleanup either... either way is fine by me.

I'm just saying the readability/error-prone improvement is *very* small - and that's *often* the case when you approach "cleanup" from a grammatical instead of a conceptual POV. Loose the forest from the trees and all that...

But even then, even if it was a substantial readability/maintainability improvement, I am *still* suggesting a proper review requires a non-trivial effort to validate this kind of change so you want that to be proportional to it's value?

... so I'd like more information.

I want to understand more about the compatibility improvement referenced in the commit message.

Hopefully the author is willing to oblige and elaborate (or another reviewer may see it and provide some context); of if everyone agrees the value is minimal we can find something with better value to work on!  Hooray!'}, {'account_id': 18820, 'date': '2015-10-16 20:45:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Changing to -1, not based on correctness, but whether change is justified by potential improvement vs. risk.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-22 10:48:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 18600, 'date': '2015-11-26 14:27:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Hi Guys!

Forget about the compability thing for a sec. Consider it as a slip of the tongue.
But lets bring in an other aspect. Assume that we have the following code:

string = "Hello world!"
if string[:5] == "Hello"
  print("match")

If somebody decides to change the comparison for some reason to e.g. string[:5] == "Hello world" then there is a chance that the left side will remain unchanged. This change won't cause any errors because the code is still valid but it will alter the behavior of the program.

Obviously, one can forget things like this as we are all humans. However, fixing these kinds of problems is the most time demanding task.'}, {'account_id': 18600, 'date': '2015-11-26 15:25:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-26 16:22:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Ok, I think the commit message is more clear - I'm more neutral on this change - I'll +2 and let someone else comment.

I really think that the pep was only suggesting it's generally more readable to use startswith/endswith in place of *string slicing* (an index that includes a ":") - and I whole heartedly agree.

In fact there's a few places in this cleanup that catch some poor use of slicing - and I also like using the truthyness of non-empty strings over converting to the truthyness of integers with len (also recommended against in the pep).

commit_message:
Replace string slicing with proper string methods

Updated string prefix and suffix checker slicing to startswith()
and endswith() methods.

Using startswith() and endswith() improves readability, error-proneness
and enhances maintainability.

Change-Id: I1d5fbf116a61763346c6f92fd8023dbbe9bb37cf

commit_message:
Updated flat networking docs

The change updates and corrects a couple of issues with the
documenation on the flat network setup. This should help
clarify what is needed to get a combined vlan and flat
network topology running within OSA using neutron.

Change-Id: I1591609c917db19378aa1e3479c13f11d0c55085
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Tidy up notification_driver implementation across projects

The various os_* roles implement the notification driver in
the config files in a number of different ways.

This commit standardises the implementation.

Some of the decisions that were made here (remove the variables for
the driver altogether, do not configure notifications at all if not
ceilometer) are based on an irc discussion and the outcomes.

The following variables have been removed:
 - glance_ceilometer_notification_driver
 - glance_notification_driver
 - neutron_notification_driver

If these items need to be set differently, the config_override
facility may be used.

UpgradeImpact
Bug: #1522506
Change-Id: I1ac7648a545c35f8f77d79f9cb0d9021bdb9e653

commit_message:
Add a separate get_class_to_instantiate() method to Environment

We were previously using get_class for two different purposes - to get a
resource plugin on which we could perform introspection to obtain the
properties and attributes schema, and to get a resource plugin we could
instantiate to create a Resource object. These are both the same except in
the case of a TemplateResource, where having two different use cases for
the same piece of code was adding considerable extra complexity. Combining
the use cases in this way also made the error handling confusing (leading
to bug 1518458).

This change separates out the two cases.

Change-Id: I3bde081cd4537810c8c6a0948ab447c3fb7ca9bc
Related-Bug: #1447194
Related-Bug: #1518458
Related-Bug: #1508115

commit_message:
Group config params more logically

We have a number of parameters that are related - network_gateway
is often set to local_ip, masquerade_network is almost always
network_cidr, so it makes sense to group those params close to
each other so users see them one after the other.

Change-Id: Icd83d2587ed9bb2152296ba6edd5cf3c7daa768a

commit_message:
Get reserved host memory for nova-compute

Get reserved host memory straight value for nova-compute if we have Ceph
OSD neighbor resides on the same node.
The formula is:
  * min default value = 512Mb
  * max value = 1.5Gb
  * straight value = 20% of total memory

Closes-Bug: #1507306
Change-Id: I6a58095825d248ba40d6cecd983812dd3e17abb7

commit_message:
Change firewall rules for UI https port to less strict ones

Open UI for have an ability to reach it from non-admin network, as user can
have several networks on master node from which he have to have access to UI.

Change-Id: Ieab40fae513e65784cb36a6d0a43ff794a82b030
Closes-Bug: #1521557

commit_message:
Add support for configuration groups in int-tests

Datastore agnostic support was added for configuration
groups in the int-tests.  The new groups was added to
the supported int-tests for Cassandra, Redis and MongoDB.

The tests can be run by:
./redstack int-tests --group=configuration
                 (or --group=<datastore>_supported)

Co-Authored-By: Petr Malik <pmalik@tesora.com>
Co-Authored-By: Peter Stachowski <peter@tesora.com>
Change-Id: I052636ff937604a31d41b53767a3cd4e6b9979a5

commit_message:
Document setting capabilities in JSON

This can be an easier way of setting node profiles or any other
custom capabilities that a user may want.

commit_message:
Make add_member use **kwargs and doc string update

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.

This patch makes add_member use **kwargs.
Also update doc string for the same.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I67810b4e9c313611393e896f68d3b4a1dda77bea

commit_message:
Add keymgr/encryption_auth_url parameter to cinder API

This value defaults to http://localhost:5000/v3, which works for many
deployments, but if Keystone is located on a separate node,
cinder quota-show $PROJECT_ID fails to contact keystone.

More info about this bug at LP #1516085
Partial-Bug: #1521640

Change-Id: I3457e60e8ce5f2df0830b45c3d18caa88e40f040

Remove unnecessary constants

This patch removes the unused constants values. Some of them are
for the old libnetwork API spec and totally obsolete.

Change-Id: I4dd13903cbe9e2059c8bdadf7f13ea42d820b82e
Signed-off-by: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1523388

commit_message:
Fix the wrong selinux context when glance uses nfs backend

We updated the pacemaker resource configuration
of fs-varlibglanceimages-clone to mount nfs directory
with a specified context.

Details on : https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1237150

Change-Id: Ia0dd471858f470ae3e82d25151ebe65b8cdbec4f

commit_message:
Add fuelmenu-rsync command

* fuelmenu-rsync is now available. It allows to rsync code from root of
fuel-menu repository to master node.
* Refactored RsyncCommand - moved it from docker module to command
  module, so it can be used not only for docker-related rsyncing.

Change-Id: I3dcfa2d00a22368ce40e8457c3aacb72700bc54f
Closes-bug: #1522441

commit_message:
Implementation of router bgpvpn associations.

This commit implements bp router-bgpvpn-association. Router associations
will work similar to network associations except in the bagpipe driver where
the router association will in fact get translated into multiple network
assocations.

Implements: blueprint router-bgpvpn-association
Change-Id: Ia9db2b64bcf0cdcc25e4154eeb557073be9f2221

commit_message:
Add unit test for test_servers_client-allfunctions

We have a plan to migrate service clients to tempest-lib from Tempest.
However, we are not doing enough tests for service clients now.
This patch adds unit test for test_servers_client (all functions)

commit_message:
Allow creating an Opt with type=str

Commit 545dd4113e62f8f4aa8b6f147e7c80ce8d460975 broke config file
generation for a number of projects. The reason for this is that
config options created by keystoneauth with type=str (see
https://github.com/openstack/keystoneauth/blob/master/keystoneauth1/loading/opts.py#L68)
did not have a format_defaults method.

Class Opt supports creating objects with type=None, which are
converted to types.String. We can extend this support to type=str.

Change-Id: I4a40a409cd900d166701e1860daea1def6ce4e64

[{'created': '2015-12-07 05:17:03.000000000', 'message': 'Use assertIn and assertNotIn

Tests should use:

    self.assertIn(value, list)
    self.assertNotIn(value, list)

instead of:

    self.assertTrue(value in list)
    self.assertFalse(value in list)

because assertIn and assertNotIn raise more meaningful errors:

    self.assertIn(3, [1, 2])
    >>> MismatchError: 3 not in [1, 2]

    self.assertTrue(3 in [1, 2])
    >>> AssertionError: False is not true

Change-Id: I64322073c3808a03e5a3d485a7eea257ab1403e6
Related-Bug: #1218713
'}]
commit_message:
Use assertIn and assertNotIn

Tests should use:

    self.assertIn(value, list)
    self.assertNotIn(value, list)

instead of:

    self.assertTrue(value in list)
    self.assertFalse(value in list)

because assertIn and assertNotIn raise more meaningful errors:

    self.assertIn(3, [1, 2])
    >>> MismatchError: 3 not in [1, 2]

    self.assertTrue(3 in [1, 2])
    >>> AssertionError: False is not true

Change-Id: I64322073c3808a03e5a3d485a7eea257ab1403e6
Related-Bug: #1218713

commit_message:
Add networking-bgpvpn jobs for bagpipe driver

This change defines a jenkins job template to test the installation
of the networking-bgpvpn bagpipe driver (the existing job was only
testing a dummy driver).

This template is then used to define jobs to run the checks both against
the master branch of other Openstack projects (in our case devstack and
neutron import) and against the stable/liberty branch of other Openstack
projects. The motivation for doing so was explained in detail for
I049a521b4e948a042c9b49eaecd9399cf84353d1.

Change-Id: I7273a5e486e7023a59b95a325db2e6400c209a48

commit_message:
Add registry_trust_id to bay

Registry_trust_id is used for docker registry. Magnum creates a
trust for each bay and deletes the trust after a bay is deleted.

Change-Id: I8a7975cf619d6e782729184ebef795429d13c8d0
Partially-Implements: blueprint registryv2-in-master

commit_message:
Replaces "Programs" with "Cross-project Specs" on landing

For landing page specs.openstack.org, best not to confuse
with an outdated naming convention. Would like to emphasize
cross-project nature of those specifications.

Change-Id: I342e0aa1131804af065b28226035154a6443cf07
